1
00:00:00,689 --> 00:00:30,021
Namo Tassa Bhagavato Arahato Sambha Sambhudassa Namo Tassa Bhagavato Arahato Sambha Sambhudassa Namo Tassa Bhagavato Arahato Sambha Sambhudassa Homage to the Buddha, the Blessed Noble

2
00:00:30,254 --> 00:00:31,736
And fully self-enlightened.

3
00:00:32,877 --> 00:00:36,740
Noreen keeps up her group of Skype.

4
00:00:36,761 --> 00:00:37,601
About four or five of them.

5
00:00:38,082 --> 00:00:40,185
Who discuss the Dharma.

6
00:00:40,886 --> 00:00:42,987
And they take a book or they take something.

7
00:00:44,009 --> 00:00:45,771
And this was something that came up for them.

8
00:00:46,932 --> 00:00:49,255
She sent it to me because there was a question about something.

9
00:00:49,295 --> 00:00:50,957
Which we will come to later.

10
00:00:51,457 --> 00:00:54,720
So Meichi Kyo is a Taifo Shunan.

11
00:00:54,941 --> 00:00:59,906
Who is recognized as a fully liberated being.

12
00:01:00,578 --> 00:01:08,126
And this is one of her statements, and we'll use it to find out how we can get there, even this week.

13
00:01:09,867 --> 00:01:14,272
Body, mind and essence are all distinct and separate realities.

14
00:01:16,194 --> 00:01:17,715
Absolutely everything is known.

15
00:01:18,356 --> 00:01:20,418
Earth, water, fire and wind.

16
00:01:21,519 --> 00:01:24,462
Body, feeling, memory, thought and consciousness.

17
00:01:26,444 --> 00:01:30,349
Sounds, sights, smells, tastes, touches and emotions.

18
00:01:31,662 --> 00:01:34,344
Anger, greed and delusion all are known.

19
00:01:35,346 --> 00:01:39,451
I know them all as they exist in their own natural states.

20
00:01:41,353 --> 00:01:50,646
But no matter how much I am exposed to them, I am unable to detect even an instant when they have any power over my heart.

21
00:01:52,067 --> 00:01:53,310
They arise and cease.

22
00:01:53,810 --> 00:01:55,031
They are forever changing.

23
00:01:56,093 --> 00:01:59,998
But the presence that knows them never changes for an instant.

24
00:02:01,042 --> 00:02:03,325
It is forever unborn and undying.

25
00:02:04,204 --> 00:02:08,430
This is the end of suffering.

26
00:02:08,449 --> 00:02:09,131
That's pretty clear.

27
00:02:12,534 --> 00:02:14,817
So, how do we get to this point, I wonder?

28
00:02:15,657 --> 00:02:20,663
The end of suffering.

29
00:02:20,683 --> 00:02:27,471
We'll come back to this in a moment, because if we want to teach people the Dharma,

30
00:02:27,991 --> 00:02:34,776
then we've got to be pretty clear ourselves about the basic tinnitus, the basic position of the Buddha took.

31
00:02:34,796 --> 00:02:47,870
And to actually be able to feel that you have the internal logic of his teaching, the internal rationality of his teaching, to make that bold statement, you know, there is an end of suffering.

32
00:02:48,750 --> 00:02:53,754
I don't think there's a single Western psychologist or school that says there's an end to suffering.

33
00:02:54,155 --> 00:02:56,918
They've always got maybe...

34
00:02:57,521 --> 00:02:59,465
Maybe if they were Christians, they would have thought so.

35
00:03:01,567 --> 00:03:08,917
But in the sense of there being an end of suffering right here in this very life, I think that's quite a bold statement to make.

36
00:03:11,741 --> 00:03:21,454
So, just for us to revise, really, just to go through our minds, the four basic truths that the Buddha taught.

37
00:03:22,955 --> 00:03:24,718
This truth of dukkha, you see.

38
00:03:25,239 --> 00:03:26,600
Remember, dukkha means something

39
00:03:26,850 --> 00:03:28,954
Hard to bear, that's its sort of translation.

40
00:03:29,514 --> 00:03:30,115
Hard to bear.

41
00:03:31,317 --> 00:03:42,610
It's not only referring to the pains and aches of the body and the emotional upsets, the pressures and the stress of life.

42
00:03:43,712 --> 00:03:46,075
It always boils down to these three characteristics.

43
00:03:47,056 --> 00:03:56,149
That our deep suffering, the deeper level of existential suffering, comes about because we're not actually seeing things as they really are.

44
00:03:56,415 --> 00:03:58,078
That's his normal statement.

45
00:03:58,699 --> 00:04:07,810
Now that statement, which is a translation of the Pali, isn't actually absolutely correct.

46
00:04:08,191 --> 00:04:13,397
The translation is to see and understand how things have come to be.

47
00:04:14,318 --> 00:04:15,259
So this is the Buddha.

48
00:04:15,639 --> 00:04:16,862
He's interested in process.

49
00:04:17,463 --> 00:04:18,483
He's interested in process.

50
00:04:18,925 --> 00:04:25,612
So when we, today for instance, when we're just observing the process of eating, see?

51
00:04:25,829 --> 00:04:29,773
It's the whole process that we are trying to engage with, trying to understand.

52
00:04:29,793 --> 00:04:41,184
How is it that we create this world within this psychophysical organism, this body and mind, this fathom-length body, as the Buddha puts it.

53
00:04:41,865 --> 00:04:46,108
Within this fathom-length body is the world, the creation of the world, etc., etc.

54
00:04:47,350 --> 00:04:55,177
And it's really beginning to understand that we are limited by the body.

55
00:04:55,747 --> 00:04:58,091
as to what we can experience anyway.

56
00:04:58,711 --> 00:05:08,702
And then whatever information the body gives us is always taken inward and fixed into our concepts about things.

57
00:05:09,543 --> 00:05:13,507
And these concepts about things are built up from past perceptions.

58
00:05:14,088 --> 00:05:17,853
So, very simply, today we had chili beans, you see.

59
00:05:18,353 --> 00:05:21,757
Well, we've probably made our own chili beans and had chili beans elsewhere.

60
00:05:22,338 --> 00:05:24,220
So as soon as we tasted these chili beans,

61
00:05:24,588 --> 00:05:54,223
we knew whether they were the real chili beans or not because either they're not the proper chili beans or they are the proper chili beans or they're almost the proper chili beans so it's this judging mind and that's something else remember judging there's a distinction between judging and judgmental but putting that aside this whole process of creating the world within ourselves having this

62
00:05:54,524 --> 00:06:23,973
memory of past events reliving really the world through our particular memory patterns and that's the sankaras that's our habits see so when the buddha talks about this dukkha he's sort of digging deep at the level of our perception how we perceive things and one of them is that we perceive continuity and we actually really do believe that you know

63
00:06:24,307 --> 00:06:29,713
The person, me, who got up this morning, well, I'm pretty well the same person now.

64
00:06:30,355 --> 00:06:35,079
I don't see, I don't experience myself arising and passing away.

65
00:06:35,261 --> 00:06:40,305
I experience myself as absolutely constant within a mass of change.

66
00:06:40,766 --> 00:06:43,230
It's me always that's doing stuff.

67
00:06:43,250 --> 00:06:53,742
And it's getting down to that anicca, getting down to this real deep level of impermanence is to see that the actual self is arising and passing away, the sense of me

68
00:06:54,194 --> 00:06:59,160
arises with every experience I'm having, momentary experience I'm having.

69
00:06:59,740 --> 00:07:05,088
So, this again digs even deeper to the point of identity.

70
00:07:06,389 --> 00:07:15,240
Now, here in this statement, you see, she says, I am unable to detect, even for an instant, when they have any power over my heart.

71
00:07:15,942 --> 00:07:19,947
See, to have power is to have control, it's the self.

72
00:07:20,607 --> 00:07:23,391
Whenever you say, you know, this is me,

73
00:07:23,826 --> 00:07:25,028
and then you define it.

74
00:07:25,168 --> 00:07:41,850
If you say, I am, and you put something at the end of that sentence, I am angry, I am happy, I am an engineer, I am a nurse, whatever you say after that, you're locked into that definition, even if only for that moment, for that time.

75
00:07:42,591 --> 00:07:44,374
And that's how we define ourselves.

76
00:07:44,394 --> 00:07:51,622
When that definition disappears, then of course at times it can send us into a process of not knowing who we are.

77
00:07:51,906 --> 00:07:54,488
So you get this crisis, an identity crisis.

78
00:07:55,410 --> 00:07:57,591
I remember that I used to have a Tai Chi teacher.

79
00:07:57,612 --> 00:07:58,233
He was a lovely man.

80
00:07:58,973 --> 00:08:02,257
And I stopped going.

81
00:08:02,276 --> 00:08:03,658
And I met him years on.

82
00:08:04,259 --> 00:08:06,261
Well, not that far on, maybe two or three years on.

83
00:08:06,680 --> 00:08:08,562
And he was half the man I remember him.

84
00:08:08,903 --> 00:08:09,923
And I said, what's happened?

85
00:08:09,963 --> 00:08:10,964
I thought he'd had an illness.

86
00:08:11,505 --> 00:08:13,067
He said, no, he just lost his job.

87
00:08:13,927 --> 00:08:15,288
So with his job, lost his debt.

88
00:08:15,348 --> 00:08:19,432
It wasn't only the pain of loss of the income, you know, which we were finding out.

89
00:08:19,783 --> 00:08:26,531
But the whole self-definition of who he was and what his position was in the world, it was just taken away from him.

90
00:08:26,550 --> 00:08:32,756
And he had the usual depression and all that sort of stuff that comes with that loss of identity.

91
00:08:34,239 --> 00:08:39,004
And of course, the final loss of identity is when they lay us out in the morgue.

92
00:08:39,024 --> 00:08:41,306
I mean, that's when we know we've lost our identity.

93
00:08:43,008 --> 00:08:49,234
So the way the Buddha sort of digs really deep, and it's a place, of course, that

94
00:08:50,158 --> 00:09:18,697
most therapies don't want to go it's a bit frightening to get down to that level but that's where we want to get to we want to get down to this business of who am I before I describe myself before there's something coming after the am I am whatever and it's because remember because of this deep delusion as to who I am meaning this body, this heart, this mind this person see this person

95
00:09:19,774 --> 00:09:21,456
Which exists, by the way.

96
00:09:21,476 --> 00:09:25,280
The person exists in the sense that it's momentary.

97
00:09:25,480 --> 00:09:31,388
It's a momentary total conception of me.

98
00:09:32,208 --> 00:09:35,611
There are experiences in meditation where you can step out of the self.

99
00:09:35,732 --> 00:09:40,898
It's a bit strange, but you can step out of it and you see, oh, there's the self.

100
00:09:41,379 --> 00:09:43,280
And that self, but it's not permanent.

101
00:09:43,341 --> 00:09:44,001
That's the problem.

102
00:09:44,741 --> 00:09:47,065
Now, because of this identity thing,

103
00:09:47,381 --> 00:09:54,812
of this identity of being this person, then remember that I have this relationship with the world now.

104
00:09:55,393 --> 00:09:58,597
And when we ask ourselves, how do I want to be?

105
00:09:59,259 --> 00:10:01,120
How do I want to be?

106
00:10:01,741 --> 00:10:02,543
What do I want to be?

107
00:10:02,923 --> 00:10:04,745
I think we've come to this word, happy.

108
00:10:04,785 --> 00:10:08,652
I just want to be happy, for heaven's sake.

109
00:10:09,153 --> 00:10:16,663
Everybody will define their happiness in their own way, but that I want to be happy is just, that's all I want to be.

110
00:10:16,980 --> 00:10:46,886
you want to be happy and because of this delusion though remember we seek the happiness in in just these wrong places and and that's where we form attachments and attachments are simply our psychological dependency on something and then we find we don't have control over it and so and so the whole gamut of human misery starts you know the frustration grief etc and of course once you once you've gained something you've got to protect it one way or the other you know whether it's against

111
00:10:47,068 --> 00:10:52,735
some nasty person or a government, you've got to protect what you have.

112
00:10:53,235 --> 00:10:56,519
And so there's that aversion and the fear of loss.

113
00:10:56,538 --> 00:11:03,285
So you can see from this deep delusion that arises a more tangible dukkha.

114
00:11:03,947 --> 00:11:06,570
I mean, if you were to say to somebody, are you suffering?

115
00:11:06,610 --> 00:11:13,397
They'd probably point to these sorts of things, you know, like I'm depressed, my job's not going well, my relationship's collapsing, all that sort of stuff.

116
00:11:13,731 --> 00:11:43,602
so they're pointing to something actually concrete and something they can actually feel and explain but at a deeper level we have this inexplicable sense of identity you see and you can see from her statement that something's missing there isn't it because no matter what's happening to her at any level it doesn't have any power over her heart in other words

117
00:11:43,820 --> 00:11:45,721
She cannot be grasped by it.

118
00:11:46,341 --> 00:11:47,543
She cannot be lost in it.

119
00:11:47,583 --> 00:11:48,563
Deluded by it.

120
00:11:50,426 --> 00:11:50,947
So that's.

121
00:11:51,086 --> 00:11:53,349
That's where the Buddha puts his.

122
00:11:53,369 --> 00:11:54,549
You know.

123
00:11:55,490 --> 00:11:57,773
Stakes out his cause.

124
00:11:58,192 --> 00:11:59,315
There is Dukkha.

125
00:12:00,254 --> 00:12:00,995
And there's no way.

126
00:12:01,035 --> 00:12:02,677
There can't be Dukkha.

127
00:12:02,918 --> 00:12:03,498
That's the point.

128
00:12:03,518 --> 00:12:04,318
There's no way.

129
00:12:05,941 --> 00:12:06,400
For us.

130
00:12:07,201 --> 00:12:08,722
With the idea of a self.

131
00:12:09,344 --> 00:12:11,686
There can be anything but Dukkha in the end.

132
00:12:12,066 --> 00:12:13,707
And even when we are.

133
00:12:13,942 --> 00:12:43,812
totally happy when things are going perfectly right and the world is full of gold and shining there is always that awful feeling underneath that things are passing that you don't have control over it so nothing can give us absolute total satisfaction again it's usually expressed in the negative the presence that knows them never changes for an instant

134
00:12:44,451 --> 00:12:46,073
See, this is the end of suffering.

135
00:12:46,815 --> 00:13:03,879
So, in terms of how we would normally define our happiness, normally define a state of adukha, not suffering, we would normally define it in a very positive way, such as, you know, feeling happy, going on holiday, having a good job, all that sort of stuff.

136
00:13:04,259 --> 00:13:11,688
We would actually define it as some sort of existing experience.

137
00:13:12,129 --> 00:13:14,273
But this can't be that, can it?

138
00:13:15,028 --> 00:13:17,250
Because she's opted out of all experiences.

139
00:13:17,270 --> 00:13:18,712
This is a presence that knows.

140
00:13:19,312 --> 00:13:20,634
Never changes for an instant.

141
00:13:21,335 --> 00:13:22,956
It's forever unborn and undying.

142
00:13:23,017 --> 00:13:23,418
In other words.

143
00:13:23,437 --> 00:13:24,798
It's not part of the process.

144
00:13:25,219 --> 00:13:26,441
Of the phenomenal world.

145
00:13:26,520 --> 00:13:27,581
That we're experiencing.

146
00:13:27,662 --> 00:13:29,464
Which is arising and passing away.

147
00:13:31,745 --> 00:13:32,746
Complete distinct from it.

148
00:13:32,947 --> 00:13:34,128
This is the end of suffering.

149
00:13:34,568 --> 00:13:34,828
So.

150
00:13:36,770 --> 00:13:37,692
Our question is then.

151
00:13:37,751 --> 00:13:38,692
What is.

152
00:13:38,732 --> 00:13:41,535
The next position that the Buddha takes is.

153
00:13:41,755 --> 00:13:42,697
What's the cause of it?

154
00:13:43,337 --> 00:13:43,618
Now.

155
00:13:43,970 --> 00:13:58,107
He doesn't, having stated these three delusions of Anitta, Dukkha and Atta, he doesn't drive at the cause, this is an important point, he doesn't drive at the cause of being, the problem is identity.

156
00:13:58,587 --> 00:14:05,115
That's not where he's positioning us because that would be impossible to work with directly.

157
00:14:05,937 --> 00:14:12,846
He's pointing to how this delusion and this wrong identity manifests

158
00:14:13,163 --> 00:14:14,803
And it manifests in our desires.

159
00:14:16,105 --> 00:14:19,168
So then he gives us this dependent origination.

160
00:14:19,849 --> 00:14:21,230
Which is in the second noble truth.

161
00:14:21,269 --> 00:14:28,596
He tries to point out to us where the weak link is in this whole process of creating suffering for ourselves.

162
00:14:29,336 --> 00:14:32,620
And you'll notice that at the base you've got this sense of ignorance.

163
00:14:33,159 --> 00:14:35,562
Now remember that ignorance is not culpable.

164
00:14:35,621 --> 00:14:37,803
It's not as though we should have known better.

165
00:14:38,365 --> 00:14:40,025
It's a state of not knowing.

166
00:14:40,687 --> 00:14:42,427
And just like we don't know some things.

167
00:14:42,796 --> 00:15:11,436
we then presume to know or we think we know or we make a guess or we take a leap and it's usually into some sort of pit see so it's accepting that at the base of our the fundamental part of us is a state of not knowing and this remember translates into the heart as a sense of innocence so from a moral heart point of view you know compassion joy and peace

168
00:15:11,720 --> 00:15:16,464
We start from the point of innocence, which means not doing harm.

169
00:15:16,683 --> 00:15:18,645
It's the Latin, no harm.

170
00:15:19,245 --> 00:15:31,976
So there's no harm and not knowing are combined to form what she's referring to here as body-mind, mind especially.

171
00:15:33,418 --> 00:15:36,301
I don't know what words she's referring to in the Pali.

172
00:15:36,900 --> 00:15:41,625
The Buddha uses words contextually

173
00:15:42,027 --> 00:15:47,034
Sometimes they seem to contradict each other if you're actually going just for a word.

174
00:15:47,816 --> 00:15:50,299
So take the word chitta.

175
00:15:50,759 --> 00:16:00,053
Chitta could be translated in our language as the combination of mind and heart.

176
00:16:00,575 --> 00:16:03,158
The old word soul as opposed to spirit.

177
00:16:04,640 --> 00:16:05,162
Psyche.

178
00:16:05,883 --> 00:16:10,971
We split those in our enlightenment period, you know, in the

179
00:16:11,322 --> 00:16:12,943
Great 18th century enlightenment.

180
00:16:12,964 --> 00:16:17,330
So that we think of ourselves as rational beings and or feeling beings, you know.

181
00:16:17,630 --> 00:16:22,177
So you get people say, I think, and then others say, I feel, see.

182
00:16:22,197 --> 00:16:27,604
So this split is something that we have, which has, of course, had its brighter side.

183
00:16:27,683 --> 00:16:30,226
It's brought about science and technology and all that.

184
00:16:31,269 --> 00:16:36,095
But in the Buddha's understanding, that would all be just one faculty.

185
00:16:36,495 --> 00:16:38,038
And that's known as citta, see.

186
00:16:38,575 --> 00:16:45,744
And yet in his victory verse, the one that we chant in the morning, he says he's achieved the asankatam chittam.

187
00:16:45,764 --> 00:16:48,307
So he's achieved something which is not conditioned.

188
00:16:48,407 --> 00:16:53,974
That obviously can't be the body, the mind-heart matrix.

189
00:16:55,475 --> 00:16:59,980
So we have to be careful about, I don't know what words she's referring to here.

190
00:17:02,384 --> 00:17:07,349
So we have this dependent origination, you see, and

191
00:17:07,667 --> 00:17:33,455
need to be clear about that we need to be clear as to why the buddha taught it so he's teaching us how we create the world and it's it's it's the creation in time because these these uh links uh don't always come at the same time the first the first few are always there at any given time so there's always that not knowing beneath everything we do a sense of

192
00:17:33,740 --> 00:17:37,785
which express themselves as a lack of wisdom.

193
00:17:38,566 --> 00:17:41,949
And because of that, we've created these delusions, these sankara.

194
00:17:42,650 --> 00:17:48,016
And they're running underneath every moment as a potential, like a program in a computer.

195
00:17:48,717 --> 00:17:55,625
And then you have a moment of action, a moment that drops into this flow, you might say.

196
00:17:56,605 --> 00:17:58,808
Of course, they're momentary, arising and passing away and all that.

197
00:17:58,828 --> 00:18:03,273
But even so, you've got this drop into the moment,

198
00:18:03,472 --> 00:18:07,037
And that's when you get the body, mind and consciousness.

199
00:18:07,758 --> 00:18:09,059
And he separates them, you see.

200
00:18:09,140 --> 00:18:17,971
The body and mind are one matrix, the body and the mind working off each other.

201
00:18:18,612 --> 00:18:19,893
So that's what we do when we're eating.

202
00:18:19,932 --> 00:18:25,259
We're seeing that there's the body taste, the heart responds with a bit of joy and so on.

203
00:18:25,279 --> 00:18:31,287
So that matrix is always happening and there's the consciousness of it.

204
00:18:31,721 --> 00:18:36,988
So consciousness here, you have to be careful, it's a discriminative consciousness.

205
00:18:37,347 --> 00:18:47,579
There is included in there, shall we say, a certain knowing, a certain habitual way of discriminating things.

206
00:18:50,202 --> 00:18:52,545
Just even at a very simple perceptual level.

207
00:18:55,188 --> 00:18:58,692
You know that when Cook arrived in Australia,

208
00:18:59,059 --> 00:19:03,204
the Aborigines didn't see the ships because they didn't have a context in which to see them.

209
00:19:03,746 --> 00:19:04,547
It's the same with me.

210
00:19:04,606 --> 00:19:07,270
When I was in Sri Lanka, I heard this barking.

211
00:19:07,451 --> 00:19:12,096
For some reason, I hadn't associated that sort of noise, barking, with monkeys.

212
00:19:12,857 --> 00:19:16,242
And when they told me it was monkeys and they were up there, for the life of me, I couldn't see them.

213
00:19:16,983 --> 00:19:19,366
And they were just amazed that I couldn't see these monkeys.

